# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: inorganic-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] In inorganic chemistry, **crystal field theory** (**CFT**) describes the breaking of degeneracies of electron orbital states, usually *d* or *f* orbitals, due to a static electric field produced by a surrounding charge distribution (anion neighbors).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] This theory has been used to describe various spectroscopies of transition metal coordination complexes, in particular optical spectra (colors).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] CFT successfully accounts for some magnetic properties, colors, hydration enthalpies, and spinel structures of transition metal complexes, but it does not attempt to describe bonding.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] CFT was developed by physicists Hans Bethe and John Hasbrouck van Vleck in the 1930s.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] CFT was subsequently combined with molecular orbital theory to form the more realistic and complex ligand field theory (LFT), which delivers insight into the process of chemical bonding in transition metal complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] CFT can be complicated further by breaking assumptions made of relative metal and ligand orbital energies, requiring the use of inverted ligand field theory (ILFT) to better describe bonding.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] According to crystal field theory, the interaction between a transition metal and ligands arises from the attraction between the positively charged metal cation and the negative charge on the non-bonding electrons of the ligand.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The theory is developed by considering energy changes of the five degenerate *d*-orbitals upon being surrounded by an array of point charges consisting of the ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] As a ligand approaches the metal ion, the electrons from the ligand will be closer to some of the *d*-orbitals and farther away from others, causing a loss of degeneracy.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The electrons in the *d*-orbitals and those in the ligand repel each other due to repulsion between like charges.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Thus the d-electrons closer to the ligands will have a higher energy than those further away which results in the *d*-orbitals splitting in energy.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The most common type of complex is octahedral, in which six ligands form the vertices of an octahedron around the metal ion.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The three lower-energy orbitals are collectively referred to as **t2g**, and the two higher-energy orbitals as **eg**.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] These labels are based on the theory of molecular symmetry: they are the names of irreducible representations of the octahedral point group, Oh.(see the Oh character table) Typical orbital energy diagrams are given below in the section High-spin and low-spin.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Tetrahedral complexes are the second most common type; here four ligands form a tetrahedron around the metal ion.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] In a tetrahedral crystal field splitting, the *d*-orbitals again split into two groups, with an energy difference of **Δtet**.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The lower energy orbitals will be *d**z*2 and *d**x*2-*y*2, and the higher energy orbitals will be *d**xy*, *d**xz* and *d**yz* - opposite to the octahedral case.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Furthermore, since the ligand electrons in tetrahedral symmetry are not oriented directly towards the *d*-orbitals, the energy splitting will be lower than in the octahedral case.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Square planar and other complex geometries can also be described by CFT.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The size of the gap Δ between the two or more sets of orbitals depends on several factors, including the ligands and geometry of the complex.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Some ligands always produce a small value of Δ, while others always give a large splitting.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The reasons behind this can be explained by ligand field theory.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] It is useful to note that the ligands producing the most splitting are those that can engage in metal to ligand back-bonding.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The oxidation state of the metal also contributes to the size of Δ between the high and low energy levels.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] As the oxidation state increases for a given metal, the magnitude of Δ increases.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] A V3+ complex will have a larger Δ than a V2+ complex for a given set of ligands, as the difference in charge density allows the ligands to be closer to a V3+ ion than to a V2+ ion.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The smaller distance between the ligand and the metal ion results in a larger Δ, because the ligand and metal electrons are closer together and therefore repel more.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Ligands which cause a large splitting Δ of the *d*-orbitals are referred to as strong-field ligands, such as CN− and CO from the spectrochemical series.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] In complexes with these ligands, it is unfavourable to put electrons into the high energy orbitals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Therefore, the lower energy orbitals are completely filled before population of the upper sets starts according to the Aufbau principle.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Complexes such as this are called "low spin".
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] For example, NO2− is a strong-field ligand and produces a large Δ.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The octahedral ion [Fe(NO2)6]3−, which has 5 *d*-electrons, would have the octahedral splitting diagram shown at right with all five electrons in the *t*2*g* level.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] This low spin state therefore does not follow Hund's rule.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Conversely, ligands (like I− and Br−) which cause a small splitting Δ of the *d*-orbitals are referred to as weak-field ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] In this case, it is easier to put electrons into the higher energy set of orbitals than it is to put two into the same low-energy orbital, because two electrons in the same orbital repel each other.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] So, one electron is put into each of the five *d*-orbitals in accord with Hund's rule, and "high spin" complexes are formed before any pairing occurs.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] For example, Br− is a weak-field ligand and produces a small Δoct.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] So, the ion [FeBr6]3−, again with five *d*-electrons, would have an octahedral splitting diagram where all five orbitals are singly occupied.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] In order for low spin splitting to occur, the energy cost of placing an electron into an already singly occupied orbital must be less than the cost of placing the additional electron into an e*g* orbital at an energy cost of Δ.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] As noted above, e*g* refers to the *d**z*2 and *d**x*2-*y*2 which are higher in energy than the t2g in octahedral complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] If the energy required to pair two electrons is greater than Δ, the energy cost of placing an electron in an e*g*, high spin splitting occurs.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The crystal field splitting energy for tetrahedral metal complexes (four ligands) is referred to as Δtet, and is roughly equal to 4/9Δoct (for the same metal and same ligands).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Therefore, the energy required to pair two electrons is typically higher than the energy required for placing electrons in the higher energy orbitals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Thus, tetrahedral complexes are usually high-spin.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The use of these splitting diagrams can aid in the prediction of magnetic properties of co-ordination compounds.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] A compound that has unpaired electrons in its splitting diagram will be paramagnetic and will be attracted by magnetic fields, while a compound that lacks unpaired electrons in its splitting diagram will be diamagnetic and will be weakly repelled by a magnetic field.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The crystal field stabilization energy (CFSE) is the stability that results from placing a transition metal ion in the crystal field generated by a set of ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] It arises due to the fact that when the *d*-orbitals are split in a ligand field (as described above), some of them become lower in energy than before with respect to a spherical field known as the barycenter in which all five *d*-orbitals are degenerate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] For example, in an octahedral case, the *t2g* set becomes lower in energy than the orbitals in the barycenter.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] As a result of this, if there are any electrons occupying these orbitals, the metal ion is more stable in the ligand field relative to the barycenter by an amount known as the CFSE.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Conversely, the *eg* orbitals (in the octahedral case) are higher in energy than in the barycenter, so putting electrons in these reduces the amount of CFSE.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] If the splitting of the *d*-orbitals in an octahedral field is Δoct, the three *t2g* orbitals are stabilized relative to the barycenter by 2/5 Δoct, and the *eg* orbitals are destabilized by 3/5 Δoct.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] As examples, consider the two *d*5 configurations shown further up the page.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The low-spin (top) example has five electrons in the *t2g* orbitals, so the total CFSE is 5 x 2/5 Δoct = 2Δoct.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] In the high-spin (lower) example, the CFSE is (3 x 2/5 Δoct) - (2 x 3/5 Δoct) = 0 - in this case, the stabilization generated by the electrons in the lower orbitals is canceled out by the destabilizing effect of the electrons in the upper orbitals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] The optical properties (details of absorption and emission spectra) of many coordination complexes can be explained by Crystal Field Theory.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/crystal-field-theory] Often, however, the deeper colors of metal complexes arise from more intense charge-transfer excitations.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Many inorganic compounds are found in nature as minerals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Soil may contain iron sulfide as pyrite or calcium sulfate as gypsum.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Inorganic compounds are also found multitasking as biomolecules: as electrolytes (sodium chloride), in energy storage (ATP) or in construction (the polyphosphate backbone in DNA).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Inorganic compounds exhibit a range of bonding properties.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Some are ionic compounds, consisting of very simple cations and anions joined by ionic bonding.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Examples of salts (which are ionic compounds) are magnesium chloride MgCl2, which consists of magnesium cations Mg2+ and chloride anions Cl−; or sodium hydroxide NaOH, which consists of sodium cations Na+ and hydroxide anions OH−.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Some inorganic compounds are highly covalent, such as sulfur dioxide and iron pentacarbonyl.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Many inorganic compounds feature polar covalent bonding, which is a form of bonding intermediate between covalent and ionic bonding.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] This description applies to many oxides, carbonates, and halides.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Many inorganic compounds are characterized by high melting points.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Some salts (e.g., NaCl) are very soluble in water.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] When one reactant contains hydrogen atoms, a reaction can take place by exchanging protons in acid-base chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] In a more general definition, any chemical species capable of binding to electron pairs is called a Lewis acid; conversely any molecule that tends to donate an electron pair is referred to as a Lewis base.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] As a refinement of acid-base interactions, the HSAB theory takes into account polarizability and size of ions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Inorganic chemistry is a highly practical area of science.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Traditionally, the scale of a nation's economy could be evaluated by their productivity of sulfuric acid.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] An important man-made inorganic compound is ammonium nitrate, used for fertilization.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The ammonia is produced through the Haber process.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Nitric acid is prepared from the ammonia by oxidation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Another large-scale inorganic material is portland cement.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Inorganic compounds are used as catalysts such as vanadium(V) oxide for the oxidation of sulfur dioxide and titanium(III) chloride for the polymerization of alkenes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Many inorganic compounds are used as reagents in organic chemistry such as lithium aluminium hydride.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Descriptive inorganic chemistry focuses on the classification of compounds based on their properties.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Partly the classification focuses on the position in the periodic table of the heaviest element (the element with the highest atomic weight) in the compound, partly by grouping compounds by their structural similarities.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Classical coordination compounds feature metals bound to "lone pairs" of electrons residing on the main group atoms of ligands such as H2O, NH3, Cl−, and CN−.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] In modern coordination compounds almost all organic and inorganic compounds can be used as ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The "metal" usually is a metal from the groups 3–13, as well as the *trans*-lanthanides and *trans*-actinides, but from a certain perspective, all chemical compounds can be described as coordination complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The stereochemistry of coordination complexes can be quite rich, as hinted at by Werner's separation of two enantiomers of [Co((OH)2Co(NH3)4)3]6+, an early demonstration that chirality is not inherent to organic compounds.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] A topical theme within this specialization is supramolecular coordination chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Coordination compounds show a rich diversity of structures, varying from tetrahedral for titanium (e.g., TiCl4) to square planar for some nickel complexes to octahedral for coordination complexes of cobalt.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] A range of transition metals can be found in biologically important compounds, such as iron in hemoglobin.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] These species feature elements from groups I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII, 0 (excluding hydrogen) of the periodic table.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Due to their often similar reactivity, the elements in group 3 (Sc, Y, and La) and group 12 (Zn, Cd, and Hg) are also generally included, and the lanthanides and actinides are sometimes included as well.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Main group compounds have been known since the beginnings of chemistry, e.g., elemental sulfur and the distillable white phosphorus.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Experiments on oxygen, O2, by Lavoisier and Priestley not only identified an important diatomic gas, but opened the way for describing compounds and reactions according to stoichiometric ratios.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The discovery of a practical synthesis of ammonia using iron catalysts by Carl Bosch and Fritz Haber in the early 1900s deeply impacted mankind, demonstrating the significance of inorganic chemical synthesis.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Typical main group compounds are SiO2, SnCl4, and N2O.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Many main group compounds can also be classed as "organometallic", as they contain organic groups, e.g., B(CH3)3.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Main group compounds also occur in nature, e.g., phosphate in DNA, and therefore may be classed as bioinorganic.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Conversely, organic compounds lacking (many) hydrogen ligands can be classed as "inorganic", such as the fullerenes, buckytubes and binary carbon oxides.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Noble gas compounds include several derivatives of xenon and krypton.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Usually, organometallic compounds are considered to contain the M-C-H group.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The metal (M) in these species can either be a main group element or a transition metal.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Operationally, the definition of an organometallic compound is more relaxed to include also highly lipophilic complexes such as metal carbonyls and even metal alkoxides.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Organometallic compounds are mainly considered a special category because organic ligands are often sensitive to hydrolysis or oxidation, necessitating that organometallic chemistry employs more specialized preparative methods than was traditional in Werner-type complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Synthetic methodology, especially the ability to manipulate complexes in solvents of low coordinating power, enabled the exploration of very weakly coordinating ligands such as hydrocarbons, H2, and N2.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Because the ligands are petrochemicals in some sense, the area of organometallic chemistry has greatly benefited from its relevance to industry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Clusters can be found in all classes of chemical compounds.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] According to the commonly accepted definition, a cluster consists minimally of a triangular set of atoms that are directly bonded to each other.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] But metal–metal bonded dimetallic complexes are highly relevant to the area.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Clusters occur in "pure" inorganic systems, organometallic chemistry, main group chemistry, and bioinorganic chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The distinction between very large clusters and bulk solids is increasingly blurred.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] This interface is the chemical basis of nanoscience or nanotechnology and specifically arise from the study of quantum size effects in cadmium selenide clusters.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Thus, large clusters can be described as an array of bound atoms intermediate in character between a molecule and a solid.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] By definition, these compounds occur in nature, but the subfield includes anthropogenic species, such as pollutants (e.g., methylmercury) and drugs (e.g., Cisplatin).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Traditionally bioinorganic chemistry focuses on electron- and energy-transfer in proteins relevant to respiration.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Medicinal inorganic chemistry includes the study of both non-essential and essential elements with applications to diagnosis and therapies.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] This important area focuses on structure, bonding, and the physical properties of materials.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] In practice, solid state inorganic chemistry uses techniques such as crystallography to gain an understanding of the properties that result from collective interactions between the subunits of the solid.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Included in solid state chemistry are metals and their alloys or intermetallic derivatives.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Related fields are condensed matter physics, mineralogy, and materials science.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] In contrast to most organic compounds, many inorganic compounds are magnetic and/or colored.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] These properties provide information on the bonding and structure.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The magnetism of inorganic compounds can be complex.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] For example, most copper(II) compounds are paramagnetic but CuII2(OAc)4(H2O)2 is almost diamagnetic below room temperature.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The explanation is due to magnetic coupling between pairs of Cu(II) sites in the acetate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Inorganic chemistry has greatly benefited from qualitative theories.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Such theories are easier to learn as they require little background in quantum theory.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Within main group compounds, VSEPR theory powerfully predicts, or at least rationalizes, the structures of main group compounds, such as an explanation for why NH3 is pyramidal whereas ClF3 is T-shaped.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] For the transition metals, crystal field theory allows one to understand the magnetism of many simple complexes, such as why [FeIII(CN)6]3− has only one unpaired electron, whereas [FeIII(H2O)6]3+ has five.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] A particularly powerful qualitative approach to assessing the structure and reactivity begins with classifying molecules according to electron counting, focusing on the numbers of valence electrons, usually at the central atom in a molecule.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] A construct in chemistry is molecular symmetry, as embodied in Group theory.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Inorganic compounds display a particularly diverse symmetries, so it is logical that Group Theory is intimately associated with inorganic chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Group theory provides the language to describe the shapes of molecules according to their point group symmetry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Group theory also enables factoring and simplification of theoretical calculations.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Spectroscopic features are analyzed and described with respect to the symmetry properties of the, *inter alia*, vibrational or electronic states.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Knowledge of the symmetry properties of the ground and excited states allows one to predict the numbers and intensities of absorptions in vibrational and electronic spectra.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] A classic application of group theory is the prediction of the number of C–O vibrations in substituted metal carbonyl complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The most common applications of symmetry to spectroscopy involve vibrational and electronic spectra.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Group theory highlights commonalities and differences in the bonding of otherwise disparate species.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] For example, the metal-based orbitals transform identically for WF6 and W(CO)6, but the energies and populations of these orbitals differ significantly.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] A similar relationship exists between CO2 and molecular beryllium difluoride.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] An alternative quantitative approach to inorganic chemistry focuses on energies of reactions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] This approach is highly traditional and empirical, but it is also useful.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Broad concepts that are couched in thermodynamic terms include redox potential, acidity, phase changes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] A classic concept in inorganic thermodynamics is the Born–Haber cycle, which is used for assessing the energies of elementary processes such as electron affinity, some of which cannot be observed directly.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] An important aspect of inorganic chemistry focuses on reaction pathways, i.e. reaction mechanisms.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The mechanisms of main group compounds of groups 13–18 are usually discussed in the context of organic chemistry (organic compounds are main group compounds, after all).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Elements heavier than C, N, O, and F often form compounds with more electrons than predicted by the octet rule, as explained in the article on hypervalent molecules.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The mechanisms of their reactions differ from organic compounds for this reason.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Elements lighter than carbon (B, Be, Li) as well as Al and Mg often form electron-deficient structures that are electronically akin to carbocations.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Such electron-deficient species tend to react via associative pathways.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The chemistry of the lanthanides mirrors many aspects of chemistry seen for aluminium.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Transition metal and main group compounds often react differently.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The important role of d-orbitals in bonding strongly influences the pathways and rates of ligand substitution and dissociation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] These themes are covered in articles on coordination chemistry and ligand.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Both associative and dissociative pathways are observed.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The rates of water exchange varies by 20 orders of magnitude across the periodic table, with lanthanide complexes at one extreme and Ir(III) species being the slowest.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Redox reactions are prevalent for the transition elements.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Two classes of redox reaction are considered: atom-transfer reactions, such as oxidative addition/reductive elimination, and electron-transfer.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] A fundamental redox reaction is "self-exchange", which involves the degenerate reaction between an oxidant and a reductant.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Coordinated ligands display reactivity distinct from the free ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] For example, the acidity of the ammonia ligands in [Co(NH3)6]3+ is elevated relative to NH3 itself.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Alkenes bound to metal cations are reactive toward nucleophiles whereas alkenes normally are not.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The large and industrially important area of catalysis hinges on the ability of metals to modify the reactivity of organic ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Homogeneous catalysis occurs in solution and heterogeneous catalysis occurs when gaseous or dissolved substrates interact with surfaces of solids.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Traditionally homogeneous catalysis is considered part of organometallic chemistry and heterogeneous catalysis is discussed in the context of surface science, a subfield of solid state chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] But the basic inorganic chemical principles are the same.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Transition metals, almost uniquely, react with small molecules such as CO, H2, O2, and C2H4.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] The industrial significance of these feedstocks drives the active area of catalysis.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Ligands can also undergo ligand transfer reactions such as transmetalation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Because of the diverse range of elements and the correspondingly diverse properties of the resulting derivatives, inorganic chemistry is closely associated with many methods of analysis.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Older methods tended to examine bulk properties such as the electrical conductivity of solutions, melting points, solubility, and acidity.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] With the advent of quantum theory and the corresponding expansion of electronic apparatus, new tools have been introduced to probe the electronic properties of inorganic molecules and solids.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Often these measurements provide insights relevant to theoretical models.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Although some inorganic species can be obtained in pure form from nature, most are synthesized in chemical plants and in the laboratory.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Inorganic synthetic methods can be classified roughly according to the volatility or solubility of the component reactants.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Soluble inorganic compounds are prepared using methods of organic synthesis.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] For metal-containing compounds that are reactive toward air, Schlenk line and glove box techniques are followed.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Volatile compounds and gases are manipulated in "vacuum manifolds" consisting of glass piping interconnected through valves, the entirety of which can be evacuated to 0.001 mm Hg or less.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Compounds are condensed using liquid nitrogen (b.p.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Solids are typically prepared using tube furnaces, the reactants and products being sealed in containers, often made of fused silica (amorphous SiO2) but sometimes more specialized materials such as welded Ta tubes or Pt "boats".
[src:inorganic-chemistry/inorganic-chemistry] Products and reactants are transported between temperature zones to drive reactions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In chemistry, a **salt** or **ionic compound** is a chemical compound consisting of an assembly of positively charged ions (cations) and negatively charged ions (anions), which results in a compound with no net electric charge.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The constituent ions are held together by electrostatic forces termed *ionic bonds*.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The component ions in a salt can be either inorganic, such as chloride (Cl−), or organic, such as acetate (CH 3COO− ).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Each ion can be either monatomic, such as sodium (Na+) and chloride (Cl−) in sodium chloride, or polyatomic, such as ammonium (NH+ 4) and carbonate (CO2− 3) ions in ammonium carbonate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts containing basic ions hydroxide (OH−) or oxide (O2−) are classified as bases, such as sodium hydroxide and potassium oxide.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Individual ions within a salt usually have multiple near neighbours, so they are not considered to be part of molecules, but instead part of a continuous three-dimensional network.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts usually form crystalline structures when solid.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts composed of small ions typically have high melting and boiling points, and are hard and brittle.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] As solids they are almost always electrically insulating, but when melted or dissolved they become highly conductive, because the ions become mobile.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Some salts have large cations, large anions, or both.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In terms of their properties, such species often are more similar to organic compounds.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Historically, salt is a subtype of ionic compound.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The term *salt* used to only refer to the ionic compound formed by neutralisation of an acid and a base.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] As the definition for acid and base expands, salt becomes synonymous with ionic compound.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] However, that distinction still persists in some literature.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In 1913 the structure of sodium chloride was determined by William Henry Bragg and his son William Lawrence Bragg.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This revealed that there were six equidistant nearest neighbours for each atom, demonstrating that the constituents were not arranged in molecules or finite aggregates, but instead as a network with long-range crystalline order.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Many other inorganic compounds were also found to have similar structural features.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] These compounds were soon described as being constituted of ions rather than neutral atoms, but proof of this hypothesis was not found until the mid-1920s, when X-ray reflection experiments (which detect the density of electrons), were performed.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Principal contributors to the development of a theoretical treatment of ionic crystal structures were Max Born, Fritz Haber, Alfred Landé, Erwin Madelung, Paul Peter Ewald, and Kazimierz Fajans.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Born predicted crystal energies based on the assumption of ionic constituents, which showed good correspondence to thermochemical measurements, further supporting the assumption.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Many metals such as the alkali metals react directly with the electronegative halogens gases to form salts.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Solid salts can form upon evaporation of solvent from their solutions once the solution is supersaturated and the solid compound nucleates.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This process occurs widely in nature and is the means of formation of the evaporite minerals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Insoluble salts can be precipitated by mixing two solutions, one containing the cation and one containing the anion.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Because all solutions are electrically neutral, the two solutions mixed must also contain counterions of the opposite charges.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] To ensure that these do not contaminate the precipitated salt, it is important to ensure they do not also precipitate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If the two solutions have hydrogen ions and hydroxide ions as the counterions, they will react with one another in what is called an acid–base reaction or a neutralization reaction to form water.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Alternately the counterions can be chosen to ensure that even when combined into a single solution they will remain soluble as spectator ions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If the solvent is water in either the evaporation or precipitation method of formation, in many cases the ionic crystal formed also includes water of crystallization, so the product is known as a hydrate, and can have very different chemical properties compared to the anhydrous material.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Molten salts will solidify on cooling to below their freezing point.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This is sometimes used for the solid-state synthesis of complex salts from solid reactants, which are first melted together.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In other cases, the solid reactants do not need to be melted, but instead can react through a solid-state reaction route.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In this method, the reactants are repeatedly finely ground into a paste and then heated to a temperature where the ions in neighboring reactants can diffuse together during the time the reactant mixture remains in the oven.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Other synthetic routes use a solid precursor with the correct stoichiometric ratio of non-volatile ions, which is heated to drive off other species.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In some reactions between highly reactive metals (usually from Group 1 or Group 2) and highly electronegative halogen gases, or water, the atoms can be ionized by electron transfer, a process thermodynamically understood using the Born–Haber cycle.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Ions in salts are primarily held together by the electrostatic forces between the charge distribution of these bodies, and in particular, the ionic bond resulting from the long-ranged Coulomb attraction between the net negative charge of the anions and net positive charge of the cations.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] There is also a small additional attractive force from van der Waals interactions which contributes only around 1–2% of the cohesive energy for small ions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When a pair of ions comes close enough for their outer electron shells (most simple ions have closed shells) to overlap, a short-ranged repulsive force occurs, due to the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The balance between these forces leads to a potential energy well with minimum energy when the nuclei are separated by a specific equilibrium distance.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If the electronic structure of the two interacting bodies is affected by the presence of one another, covalent interactions (non-ionic) also contribute to the overall energy of the compound formed.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts are rarely purely ionic, i.e. held together only by electrostatic forces.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The bonds between even the most electronegative/electropositive pairs such as those in caesium fluoride exhibit a small degree of covalency.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Conversely, covalent bonds between unlike atoms often exhibit some charge separation and can be considered to have a partial ionic character.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The circumstances under which a compound will have ionic or covalent character can typically be understood using Fajans' rules, which use only charges and the sizes of each ion.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] According to these rules, compounds with the most ionic character will have large positive ions with a low charge, bonded to a small negative ion with a high charge.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] More generally HSAB theory can be applied, whereby the compounds with the most ionic character are those consisting of hard acids and hard bases: small, highly charged ions with a high difference in electronegativities between the anion and cation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This difference in electronegativities means that the charge separation, and resulting dipole moment, is maintained even when the ions are in contact (the excess electrons on the anions are not transferred or polarized to neutralize the cations).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Although chemists classify idealized bond types as being ionic or covalent, the existence of additional types such as hydrogen bonds and metallic bonds, for example, has led some philosophers of science to suggest that alternative approaches to understanding bonding are required.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This could be by applying quantum mechanics to calculate binding energies.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The lattice energy is the summation of the interaction of all sites with all other sites.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For unpolarizable spherical ions, only the charges and distances are required to determine the electrostatic interaction energy.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For any particular ideal crystal structure, all distances are geometrically related to the smallest internuclear distance.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] So for each possible crystal structure, the total electrostatic energy can be related to the electrostatic energy of unit charges at the nearest neighboring distance by a multiplicative constant called the Madelung constant that can be efficiently computed using an Ewald sum.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When a reasonable form is assumed for the additional repulsive energy, the total lattice energy can be modelled using the Born–Landé equation, the Born–Mayer equation, or in the absence of structural information, the Kapustinskii equation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Using an even simpler approximation of the ions as impenetrable hard spheres, the arrangement of anions in these systems are often related to close-packed arrangements of spheres, with the cations occupying tetrahedral or octahedral interstices.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Depending on the stoichiometry of the salt, and the coordination (principally determined by the radius ratio) of cations and anions, a variety of structures are commonly observed, and theoretically rationalized by Pauling's rules.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Some ionic liquids, particularly with mixtures of anions or cations, can be cooled rapidly enough that there is not enough time for crystal nucleation to occur, so an ionic glass is formed (with no long-range order).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Within any crystal, there will usually be some defects.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] To maintain electroneutrality of the crystals, defects that involve loss of a cation will be associated with loss of an anion, i.e. these defects come in pairs.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Frenkel defects consist of a cation vacancy paired with a cation interstitial and can be generated anywhere in the bulk of the crystal, occurring most commonly in compounds with a low coordination number and cations that are much smaller than the anions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Schottky defects consist of one vacancy of each type, and are generated at the surfaces of a crystal, occurring most commonly in compounds with a high coordination number and when the anions and cations are of similar size.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If the cations have multiple possible oxidation states, then it is possible for cation vacancies to compensate for electron deficiencies on cation sites with higher oxidation numbers, resulting in a non-stoichiometric compound.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Another non-stoichiometric possibility is the formation of an F-center, a free electron occupying an anion vacancy.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When the compound has three or more ionic components, even more defect types are possible.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] All of these point defects can be generated via thermal vibrations and have an equilibrium concentration.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Because they are energetically costly but entropically beneficial, they occur in greater concentration at higher temperatures.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Once generated, these pairs of defects can diffuse mostly independently of one another, by hopping between lattice sites.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This defect mobility is the source of most transport phenomena within an ionic crystal, including diffusion and solid state ionic conductivity.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When vacancies collide with interstitials (Frenkel), they can recombine and annihilate one another.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Similarly, vacancies are removed when they reach the surface of the crystal (Schottky).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Defects in the crystal structure generally expand the lattice parameters, reducing the overall density of the crystal.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Defects also result in ions in distinctly different local environments, which causes them to experience a different crystal-field symmetry, especially in the case of different cations exchanging lattice sites.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This results in a different splitting of d-electron orbitals, so that the optical absorption (and hence colour) can change with defect concentration.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Ionic compounds containing hydrogen ions (H+) are classified as acids, and those containing electropositive cations and basic anions ions hydroxide (OH−) or oxide (O2−) are classified as bases.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Other ionic compounds are known as salts and can be formed by acid–base reactions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts that produce hydroxide ions when dissolved in water are called alkali salts, and salts that produce hydrogen ions when dissolved in water are called acid salts, e.g. sodium hydrogen selenite (NaHSeO3).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If the compound is the result of a reaction between a strong acid and a weak base, the result is an acid salt.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If it is the result of a reaction between a strong base and a weak acid, the result is a base salt.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If it is the result of a reaction between a strong acid and a strong base, the result is a neutral salt.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Weak acids reacted with weak bases can produce ionic compounds with both the conjugate base ion and conjugate acid ion, such as ammonium acetate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Some ions are classed as amphoteric, being able to react with either an acid or a base.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This is also true of some compounds with ionic character, typically oxides or hydroxides of less-electropositive metals (so the compound also has significant covalent character), such as zinc oxide, aluminium hydroxide, aluminium oxide and lead(II) oxide.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When simple salts dissolve, they dissociate into individual ions, which are solvated and dispersed throughout the resulting solution.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In contrast, molecular compounds, which includes most organic compounds, remain intact in solution.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The solubility of salts is highest in polar solvents (such as water) or ionic liquids, but tends to be low in nonpolar solvents (such as petrol/gasoline).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This contrast is principally because the resulting ion–dipole interactions are significantly stronger than ion-induced dipole interactions, so the heat of solution is higher.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When the oppositely charged ions in the solid ionic lattice are surrounded by the opposite pole of a polar molecule, the solid ions are pulled out of the lattice and into the liquid.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If the solvation energy exceeds the lattice energy, the negative net enthalpy change of solution provides a thermodynamic drive to remove ions from their positions in the crystal and dissolve in the liquid.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The enthalpy change of solution is usually positive for most solid solutes like salts, which means that their solubility increases when the temperature increases.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] There are some unusual salts such as calcium hydroxide, where this enthalpy change is negative and the solubility decreases with temperature.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The lattice energy, the cohesive forces between these ions within a solid, determines the solubility.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The solubility is dependent on how well each ion interacts with the solvent, so certain patterns become apparent.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, salts of sodium, potassium and ammonium are usually soluble in water.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Notable exceptions include ammonium hexachloroplatinate and potassium cobaltinitrite.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Most nitrates and many sulfates are water-soluble.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Exceptions include barium sulfate, calcium sulfate (sparingly soluble), and lead(II) sulfate, where the 2+/2− pairing leads to high lattice energies.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For similar reasons, most metal carbonates are not soluble in water.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Some soluble carbonate salts are: sodium carbonate, potassium carbonate and ammonium carbonate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Strong salts or strong electrolyte salts are chemical salts composed of strong electrolytes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] These salts dissociate completely or almost completely in water.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] They are generally odorless and nonvolatile.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Most group 1 and 2 metals form strong salts.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Strong salts are especially useful when creating conductive compounds as their constituent ions allow for greater conductivity.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Weak salts or weak electrolyte salts are composed of weak electrolytes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] These salts do not dissociate well in water.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] They are generally more volatile than strong salts.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] They may be similar in odor to the acid or base they are derived from.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, sodium acetate, CH3COONa, smells similar to acetic acid CH3COOH.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts are characteristically insulators.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Although they contain charged atoms or clusters, these materials do not typically conduct electricity to any significant extent when the substance is solid.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In order to conduct, the charged particles must be mobile rather than stationary in a crystal lattice.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This is achieved to some degree at high temperatures when the defect concentration increases the ionic mobility and solid state ionic conductivity is observed.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When the salts are dissolved in a liquid or are melted into a liquid, they can conduct electricity because the ions become completely mobile.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For this reason, molten salts and solutions containing dissolved salts (e.g., sodium chloride in water) can be used as electrolytes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This conductivity gain upon dissolving or melting is sometimes used as a defining characteristic of salts.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In some unusual salts: fast-ion conductors, and ionic glasses, one or more of the ionic components has a significant mobility, allowing conductivity even while the material as a whole remains solid.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This is often highly temperature dependent, and may be the result of either a phase change or a high defect concentration.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] These materials are used in all solid-state supercapacitors, batteries, and fuel cells, and in various kinds of chemical sensors.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Electrostatic forces between particles are strongest when the charges are high, and the distance between the nuclei of the ions is small.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In such cases, the compounds generally have very high melting and boiling points and a low vapour pressure.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Trends in melting points can be even better explained when the structure and ionic size ratio is taken into account.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Above their melting point, salts melt and become molten salts (although some salts such as aluminium chloride and iron(III) chloride show molecule-like structures in the liquid phase).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Inorganic compounds with simple ions typically have small ions, and thus have high melting points, so are solids at room temperature.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Some substances with larger ions, however, have a melting point below or near room temperature (often defined as up to 100 °C), and are termed ionic liquids.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Ions in ionic liquids often have uneven charge distributions, or bulky substituents like hydrocarbon chains, which also play a role in determining the strength of the interactions and propensity to melt.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Even when the local structure and bonding of an ionic solid is disrupted sufficiently to melt it, there are still strong long-range electrostatic forces of attraction holding the liquid together and preventing ions boiling to form a gas phase.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This means that even room temperature ionic liquids have low vapour pressures, and require substantially higher temperatures to boil.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Boiling points exhibit similar trends to melting points in terms of the size of ions and strength of other interactions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When vapourized, the ions are still not freed of one another.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, in the vapour phase sodium chloride exists as diatomic "molecules".
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Once they reach the limit of their strength, they cannot deform malleably, because the strict alignment of positive and negative ions must be maintained.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Instead the material undergoes fracture via cleavage.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] As the temperature is elevated (usually close to the melting point) a ductile–brittle transition occurs, and plastic flow becomes possible by the motion of dislocations.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The compressibility of a salt is strongly determined by its structure, and in particular the coordination number.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, halides with the caesium chloride structure (coordination number 8) are less compressible than those with the sodium chloride structure (coordination number 6), and less again than those with a coordination number of 4.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The colour of a salt is often different from the colour of an aqueous solution containing the constituent ions, or the hydrated form of the same compound.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The anions in compounds with bonds with the most ionic character tend to be colorless (with an absorption band in the ultraviolet part of the spectrum).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In compounds with less ionic character, their color deepens through yellow, orange, red, and black (as the absorption band shifts to longer wavelengths into the visible spectrum).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The absorption band of simple cations shifts toward a shorter wavelength when they are involved in more covalent interactions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This occurs during hydration of metal ions, so colorless anhydrous salts with an anion absorbing in the infrared can become colorful in solution.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts exist in many different colors, which arise either from their constituent anions, cations or solvates.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Some minerals are salts, some of which are soluble in water.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Similarly, inorganic pigments tend not to be salts, because insolubility is required for fastness.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Some organic dyes are salts, but they are virtually insoluble in water.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts can elicit all five basic tastes, e.g., salty (sodium chloride), sweet (lead diacetate, which will cause lead poisoning if ingested), sour (potassium bitartrate), bitter (magnesium sulfate), and umami or savory (monosodium glutamate).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] That slow, partial decomposition is usually accelerated by the presence of water, since hydrolysis is the other half of the reversible reaction equation of formation of weak salts.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Salts have long had a wide variety of uses and applications.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Humans have processed common salt (sodium chloride) for over 8000 years, using it first as a food seasoning and preservative, and now also in manufacturing, agriculture, water conditioning, for de-icing roads, and many other uses.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Many salts are so widely used in society that they go by common names unrelated to their chemical identity.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Examples of this include borax, calomel, milk of magnesia, muriatic acid, oil of vitriol, saltpeter, and slaked lime.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Soluble salts can easily be dissolved to provide electrolyte solutions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This is a simple way to control the concentration and ionic strength.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The concentration of solutes affects many colligative properties, including increasing the osmotic pressure, and causing freezing-point depression and boiling-point elevation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Because the solutes are charged ions they also increase the electrical conductivity of the solution.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The increased ionic strength reduces the thickness of the electrical double layer around colloidal particles, and therefore the stability of emulsions and suspensions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The chemical identity of the ions added is also important in many uses.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, fluoride containing compounds are dissolved to supply fluoride ions for water fluoridation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Solid salts have long been used as paint pigments, and are resistant to organic solvents, but are sensitive to acidity or basicity.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Since 1801 pyrotechnicians have described and widely used metal-containing salts as sources of colour in fireworks.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Under intense heat, the electrons in the metal ions or small molecules can be excited.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] These electrons later return to lower energy states, and release light with a colour spectrum characteristic of the species present.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In chemical synthesis, salts are often used as precursors for high-temperature solid-state synthesis.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Many metals are geologically most abundant as salts within ores.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] To obtain the elemental materials, these ores are processed by smelting or electrolysis, in which redox reactions occur (often with a reducing agent such as carbon) such that the metal ions gain electrons to become neutral atoms.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] According to the nomenclature recommended by IUPAC, salts are named according to their composition, not their structure.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] In the most simple case of a binary salt with no possible ambiguity about the charges and thus the stoichiometry, the common name is written using two words.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] The name of the cation (the unmodified element name for monatomic cations) comes first, followed by the name of the anion.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, MgCl2 is named magnesium chloride, and Na2SO4 is named sodium sulfate (SO2− 4, sulfate, is an example of a polyatomic ion).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] To obtain the empirical formula from these names, the stoichiometry can be deduced from the charges on the ions, and the requirement of overall charge neutrality.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] If there are multiple different cations and/or anions, multiplicative prefixes (*di-*, *tri-*, *tetra-*, ...) are often required to indicate the relative compositions, and cations then anions are listed in alphabetical order.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] When one of the ions already has a multiplicative prefix within its name, the alternate multiplicative prefixes (*bis-*, *tris-*, *tetrakis-*, ...) are used.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, Ba(BrF4)2 is named barium bis(tetrafluoridobromate).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Compounds containing one or more elements which can exist in a variety of charge/oxidation states will have a stoichiometry that depends on which oxidation states are present, to ensure overall neutrality.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] This can be indicated in the name by specifying either the oxidation state of the elements present, or the charge on the ions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Because of the risk of ambiguity in allocating oxidation states, IUPAC prefers direct indication of the ionic charge numbers.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] These are written as an arabic integer followed by the sign (... , 2−, 1−, 1+, 2+, ...) in parentheses directly after the name of the cation (without a space separating them).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, FeSO4 is named iron(2+) sulfate (with the 2+ charge on the Fe2+ ions balancing the 2− charge on the sulfate ion), whereas Fe2(SO4)3 is named iron(3+) sulfate (because the two iron ions in each formula unit each have a charge of 3+, to balance the 2− on each of the three sulfate ions).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Stock nomenclature, still in common use, writes the oxidation number in Roman numerals (... , −II, −I, 0, I, II, ...).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] So the examples given above would be named iron(II) sulfate and iron(III) sulfate respectively.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For simple ions the ionic charge and the oxidation number are identical, but for polyatomic ions they often differ.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, the uranyl(2+) ion, UO2+ 2, has uranium in an oxidation state of +6, so would be called a dioxouranium(VI) ion in Stock nomenclature.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] An even older naming system for metal cations, also still widely used, appended the suffixes *-ous* and *-ic* to the Latin root of the name, to give special names for the low and high oxidation states.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] For example, this scheme uses "ferrous" and "ferric", for iron(II) and iron(III) respectively, so the examples given above were classically named ferrous sulfate and ferric sulfate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Zwitterions contain an anionic and a cationic centre in the same molecule, but are not considered salts.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ionic-compound] Examples of zwitterions are amino acids, many metabolites, peptides, and proteins.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In coordination chemistry, a **ligand** is an ion or molecule with a functional group that binds to a central metal atom to form a coordination complex.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The bonding with the metal generally involves formal donation of one or more of the ligand's electron pairs, often through Lewis bases.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The nature of metal–ligand bonding can range from covalent to ionic.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Furthermore, the metal–ligand bond order can range from one to three.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligands are viewed as Lewis bases, although rare cases are known to involve Lewis acidic "ligands".
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Metals and metalloids are bound to ligands in almost all circumstances, although gaseous "naked" metal ions can be generated in a high vacuum.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligands in a complex dictate the reactivity of the central atom, including ligand substitution rates, the reactivity of the ligands themselves, and redox.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligand selection requires critical consideration in many practical areas, including bioinorganic and medicinal chemistry, homogeneous catalysis, and environmental chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligands are classified in many ways, including: charge, size (bulk), the identity of the coordinating atom(s), and the number of electrons donated to the metal (denticity or hapticity).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The size of a ligand is indicated by its cone angle.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The composition of coordination complexes have been known since the early 1800s, such as Prussian blue and copper vitriol.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The key breakthrough occurred when Alfred Werner reconciled formulas and isomers.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] He showed, among other things, that the formulas of many cobalt(III) and chromium(III) compounds can be understood if the metal has six ligands in an octahedral geometry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The first to use the term "ligand" were Alfred Werner and Carl Somiesky, in relation to silicon chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The theory allows one to understand the difference between coordinated and ionic chloride in the cobalt ammine chlorides and to explain many of the previously inexplicable isomers.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] He resolved the first coordination complex called hexol into optical isomers, overthrowing the theory that chirality was necessarily associated with carbon compounds.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In general, ligands are viewed as electron donors and the metals as electron acceptors, i.e., respectively, Lewis bases and Lewis acids.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] This description has been semi-quantified in many ways, e.g.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Bonding is often described using the formalisms of molecular orbital theory.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligands and metal ions can be ordered in many ways; one ranking system focuses on ligand 'hardness' (see also hard/soft acid/base theory).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Metal ions preferentially bind certain ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In general, 'hard' metal ions prefer weak field ligands, whereas 'soft' metal ions prefer strong field ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] According to the molecular orbital theory, the HOMO (Highest Occupied Molecular Orbital) of the ligand should have an energy that overlaps with the LUMO (Lowest Unoccupied Molecular Orbital) of the metal preferential.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Metal ions bound to strong-field ligands follow the Aufbau principle, whereas complexes bound to weak-field ligands follow Hund's rule.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The energy difference between these 2 sets of d-orbitals is called the splitting parameter, Δo.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The magnitude of Δo is determined by the field-strength of the ligand: strong field ligands, by definition, increase Δo more than weak field ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligands can now be sorted according to the magnitude of Δo (see the table below).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] This ordering of ligands is almost invariable for all metal ions and is called spectrochemical series.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The energy difference between these 2 sets of d-orbitals is now called Δt.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The magnitude of Δt is smaller than for Δo, because in a tetrahedral complex only 4 ligands influence the d-orbitals, whereas in an octahedral complex the d-orbitals are influenced by 6 ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] When the coordination number is neither octahedral nor tetrahedral, the splitting becomes correspondingly more complex.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] For the purposes of ranking ligands, however, the properties of the octahedral complexes and the resulting Δo has been of primary interest.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The arrangement of the d-orbitals on the central atom (as determined by the 'strength' of the ligand), has a strong effect on virtually all the properties of the resulting complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] E.g., the energy differences in the d-orbitals has a strong effect in the optical absorption spectra of metal complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] It turns out that valence electrons occupying orbitals with significant 3 d-orbital character absorb in the 400–800 nm region of the spectrum (UV–visible range).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The absorption of light (what we perceive as the color) by these electrons (that is, excitation of electrons from one orbital to another orbital under influence of light) can be correlated to the ground state of the metal complex, which reflects the bonding properties of the ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The relative change in (relative) energy of the d-orbitals as a function of the field-strength of the ligands is described in Tanabe–Sugano diagrams.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In cases where the ligand has low energy LUMO, such orbitals also participate in the bonding.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The metal–ligand bond can be further stabilised by a formal donation of electron density back to the ligand in a process known as *back-bonding.* In this case a filled, central-atom-based orbital donates density into the LUMO of the (coordinated) ligand.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Carbon monoxide is the preeminent example a ligand that engages metals via back-donation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Complementarily, ligands with low-energy filled orbitals of pi-symmetry can serve as pi-donor.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligands are classified according to the number of electrons that they "donate" to the metal.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] L ligands are represented by amines, phosphines, CO, N2, and alkenes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Examples of L ligands extend to include dihydrogen and hydrocarbons that interact by agostic interactions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] X ligands are halides and pseudohalides.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] X ligands typically are derived from anionic precursors such as chloride but includes ligands where salts of anion do not really exist such as hydride and alkyl.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Especially in the area of organometallic chemistry, ligands are classified according to the "CBC Method" for Covalent Bond Classification, as popularized by M.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Many ligands are capable of binding metal ions through multiple sites, usually because the ligands have lone pairs on more than one atom.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligands that bind via more than one atom are often termed *chelating*.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] A ligand that binds through two sites is classified as *bidentate*, and three sites as *tridentate*.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The "bite angle" refers to the angle between the two bonds of a bidentate chelate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Chelating ligands are commonly formed by linking donor groups via organic linkers.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] A classic bidentate ligand is ethylenediamine, which is derived by the linking of two ammonia groups with an ethylene (−CH2CH2−) linker.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] A classic example of a polydentate ligand is the hexadentate chelating agent EDTA, which is able to bond through six sites, completely surrounding some metals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The number of times a polydentate ligand binds to a metal centre is symbolized by "*κn*", where *n* indicates the number of sites by which a ligand attaches to a metal.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] EDTA4−, when it is hexidentate, binds as a *κ*6-ligand, the amines and the carboxylate oxygen atoms are not contiguous.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In practice, the n value of a ligand is not indicated explicitly but rather assumed.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The binding affinity of a chelating system depends on the chelating angle or bite angle.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Denticity (represented by *κ*) is nomenclature that described to the number of noncontiguous atoms of a ligand bonded to a metal.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] This descriptor is often omitted because the denticity of a ligand is often obvious.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The complex tris(ethylenediamine)cobalt(III) could be described as [Co(κ2-en)3]3+.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Complexes of polydentate ligands are called *chelate* complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] They tend to be more stable than complexes derived from monodentate ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] This enhanced stability, called the *chelate effect*, is usually attributed to effects of entropy, which favors the displacement of many ligands by one polydentate ligand.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Related to the chelate effect is the macrocyclic effect.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] A macrocyclic ligand is any large ligand that at least partially surrounds the central atom and bonds to it, leaving the central atom at the centre of a large ring.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The more rigid and the higher its denticity, the more inert will be the macrocyclic complex.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Heme is an example, in which the iron atom is at the centre of a porphyrin macrocycle, bound to four nitrogen atoms of the tetrapyrrole macrocycle.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The very stable dimethylglyoximate complex of nickel is a synthetic macrocycle derived from dimethylglyoxime.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In coordination chemistry, a trans-spanning ligand is a bidentate ligand that can span coordination positions on opposite sides of a coordination complex.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] This means that the two attachment points of the ligand are located on opposite sides of the metal center, forming a linear or near-linear arrangement.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The trans-spanning ligand bridges the two coordination positions, providing stability to the complex.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In contrast to polydentate ligands, ambidentate ligands can attach to the central atom in either one of two (or more) places, but not both.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] An example is thiocyanate, SCN−, which can attach at either the sulfur atom or the nitrogen atom.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Such compounds give rise to linkage isomerism.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Polydentate and ambidentate are therefore two different types of polyfunctional ligands (ligands with more than one functional group) which can bond to a metal center through different ligand atoms to form various isomers.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Polydentate ligands can bond through one atom AND another (or several others) at the same time, whereas ambidentate ligands bond through one atom OR another.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Proteins are complex examples of polyfunctional ligands, usually polydentate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] A bridging ligand links two or more metal centers.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Virtually all inorganic solids with simple formulas are coordination polymers, consisting of metal ion centres linked by bridging ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] This group of materials includes all anhydrous binary metal ion halides and pseudohalides.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Bridging ligands can also persist in solution.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Polyatomic ligands such as carbonate are ambidentate and thus are found to often bind to two or three metals simultaneously.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Atoms that bridge metals are sometimes indicated with the prefix "*μ*".
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Most inorganic solids are polymers by virtue of the presence of multiple bridging ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Bridging ligands, capable of coordinating multiple metal ions, have been attracting considerable interest because of their potential use as building blocks for the fabrication of functional multimetallic assemblies.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Ligands such as halides which may not be bridging in solution can become bridging in the solid state due to the energetic favorability of filling the metal's first coordination sphere in the solid state.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] While in solution, open coordination sites in the coordination sphere of a metal complex are often filled by molecules of coordinating solvents such as water, acetonitrile, or tetrahydrofuran.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Binucleating ligands bind two metal ions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Usually binucleating ligands feature bridging ligands, such as phenoxide, pyrazolate, or pyrazine, as well as other donor groups that bind to only one of the two metal ions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Some ligands can bond to a metal center through the same atom but with a different number of lone pairs.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The bond order of the metal ligand bond can be in part distinguished through the metal ligand bond angle (M−X−R).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] This bond angle is often referred to as being linear or bent with further discussion concerning the degree to which the angle is bent.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] For example, an imido ligand in the ionic form has three lone pairs.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] One lone pair is used as a sigma X donor, the other two lone pairs are available as L-type pi donors.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] If both lone pairs are used in pi bonds then the M−N−R geometry is linear.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] However, if one or both these lone pairs is nonbonding then the M−N−R bond is bent and the extent of the bend speaks to how much pi bonding there may be.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] *η*1-Nitric oxide can coordinate to a metal center in linear or bent manner.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] A spectator ligand is a tightly coordinating polydentate ligand that does not participate in chemical reactions but removes active sites on a metal.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Spectator ligands influence the reactivity of the metal center to which they are bound.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Bulky ligands are used to control the steric properties of a metal center.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] They are used for many reasons, both practical and academic.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] On the practical side, they influence the selectivity of metal catalysts, e.g., in hydroformylation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Of academic interest, bulky ligands stabilize unusual coordination sites, e.g., reactive coligands or low coordination numbers.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Often bulky ligands are employed to simulate the steric protection afforded by proteins to metal-containing active sites.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Of course excessive steric bulk can prevent the coordination of certain ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Chiral ligands are useful for inducing asymmetry within the coordination sphere.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Often the ligand is employed as an optically pure group.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In some cases, such as secondary amines, the asymmetry arises upon coordination.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Chiral ligands are used in homogeneous catalysis, such as asymmetric hydrogenation.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Non-innocent ligands bond with metals in such a manner that the distribution of electron density between the metal center and ligand is unclear.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Describing the bonding of non-innocent ligands often involves writing multiple resonance forms that have partial contributions to the overall state.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Virtually every molecule and every ion can serve as a ligand for (or "coordinate to") metals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Monodentate ligands include virtually all anions and all simple Lewis bases.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Thus, the halides and pseudohalides are important anionic ligands whereas ammonia, carbon monoxide, and water are particularly common charge-neutral ligands.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Simple organic species are also very common, be they anionic (RO− and RCO− 2) or neutral (R2O, R2S, R3−*x*NH*x*, and R3P).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The steric properties of some ligands are evaluated in terms of their cone angles.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Beyond the classical Lewis bases and anions, all unsaturated molecules are also ligands, utilizing their pi electrons in forming the coordinate bond.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Also, metals can bind to the σ bonds in for example silanes, hydrocarbons, and dihydrogen (see also: Agostic interaction).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In complexes of non-innocent ligands, the ligand is bonded to metals via conventional bonds, but the ligand is also redox-active.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The entries in the table are sorted by field strength, binding through the stated atom (i.e. as a terminal ligand).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The 'strength' of the ligand changes when the ligand binds in an alternative binding mode (e.g., when it bridges between metals) or when the conformation of the ligand gets distorted (e.g., a linear ligand that is forced through steric interactions to bind in a nonlinear fashion).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] In this table other common ligands are listed in alphabetical order.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] A **ligand exchange** (also called **ligand substitution**) is a chemical reaction in which a ligand in a compound is replaced by another.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Two general mechanisms are recognized: associative substitution or by dissociative substitution.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Associative substitution closely resembles the SN2 mechanism in organic chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] A typically smaller ligand can attach to an unsaturated complex followed by loss of another ligand.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Typically, the rate of the substitution is first order in entering ligand L and the unsaturated complex.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] Dissociative substitution is common for octahedral complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] This pathway closely resembles the SN1 mechanism in organic chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] The identity of the entering ligand does not affect the rate.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] BioLiP is a comprehensive ligand–protein interaction database, with the 3D structure of the ligand–protein interactions taken from the Protein Data Bank.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] MANORAA is a webserver for analyzing conserved and differential molecular interaction of the ligand in complex with protein structure homologs from the Protein Data Bank.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/ligand] It provides the linkage to protein targets such as its location in the biochemical pathways, SNPs and protein/RNA baseline expression in target organ.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] In chemistry and atomic physics, the **main group** is the group of elements (sometimes called the **representative elements**) whose lightest members are represented by helium, lithium, beryllium, boron, carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, and fluorine as arranged in the periodic table of the elements.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] The main group includes the elements (except hydrogen, which is sometimes excluded) in groups 1 and 2 (s-block), and groups 13 to 18 (p-block).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] The s-block elements are primarily characterised by one main oxidation state, and the p-block elements, when they have multiple oxidation states, often have common oxidation states separated by two units.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] Advances in this area are often described in the journal Main Group Chemistry.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] Main-group elements (with some of the lighter transition metals) are the most abundant elements on Earth, in the Solar System, and in the universe.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] Group 12 elements are often considered to be transition metals; however, zinc (Zn), cadmium (Cd), and mercury (Hg) share some properties of both groups, and some scientists believe they should be included in the main group.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] Occasionally, even the group 3 elements as well as the lanthanides and actinides have been included, because especially the group 3 elements and many lanthanides are electropositive elements with only one main oxidation state like the group 1 and 2 elements.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] In older nomenclature, the main-group elements are groups IA and IIA, and groups IIIB to 0 (CAS groups IIIA to VIIIA).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] Group 12 is labelled as group IIB in both systems.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/main-group-element] Group 3 is labelled as group IIIA in the older nomenclature (CAS group IIIB).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In chemistry, a **transition metal** (or **transition element**) is a chemical element in the d-block of the periodic table (groups 3 to 12), though the elements of group 12 (and less often group 3) are sometimes excluded.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The lanthanide and actinide elements (the f-block) are called **inner transition metals** and are sometimes considered to be transition metals as well.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] They are lustrous metals with good electrical and thermal conductivity.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Most (with the exception of group 11 and group 12) are hard and strong, and have high melting and boiling temperatures.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] They form compounds in any of two or more different oxidation states and bind to a variety of ligands to form coordination complexes that are often coloured.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] They form many useful alloys and are often employed as catalysts in elemental form or in compounds such as coordination complexes and oxides.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Most are strongly paramagnetic because of their unpaired d electrons, as are many of their compounds.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] All of the elements that are ferromagnetic near room temperature are transition metals (iron, cobalt and nickel) or inner transition metals (gadolinium).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] These elements are now known as the d-block.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The 2011 IUPAC *Principles of Chemical Nomenclature* describe a "transition metal" as any element in groups 3 to 12 on the periodic table.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] This corresponds exactly to the d-block elements, and many scientists use this definition.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In actual practice, the f-block lanthanide and actinide series are called "inner transition metals".
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The 2005 *Red Book* allows for the group 12 elements to be excluded, but not the 2011 *Principles*.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The IUPAC *Gold Book* defines a transition metal as "an element whose atom has a partially filled d sub-shell, or which can give rise to cations with an incomplete d sub-shell", but this definition is taken from an old edition of the *Red Book* and is no longer present in the current edition.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In the d-block, the atoms of the elements have between zero and ten d electrons.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Published texts and periodic tables show variation regarding the heavier members of group 3.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The common placement of lanthanum and actinium in these positions is not supported by physical, chemical, and electronic evidence, which overwhelmingly favour putting lutetium and lawrencium in those places.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The group 12 elements zinc, cadmium, and mercury are sometimes excluded from the transition metals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] This is because they have the electronic configuration [ ]d10s2, where the d shell is complete, and they still have a complete d shell in all their known oxidation states.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The group 12 elements Zn, Cd and Hg may therefore, under certain criteria, be classed as post-transition metals in this case.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] However, it is often convenient to include these elements in a discussion of the transition elements.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] For example, when discussing the crystal field stabilization energy of first-row transition elements, it is convenient to also include the elements calcium and zinc, as both Ca2+ and Zn2+ have a value of zero, against which the value for other transition metal ions may be compared.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Another example occurs in the Irving–Williams series of stability constants of complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Moreover, Zn, Cd, and Hg can use their d orbitals for bonding even though they are not known in oxidation states that would formally require breaking open the d-subshell, which sets them apart from the p-block elements.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The 2007 (though disputed and so far not reproduced independently) synthesis of mercury(IV) fluoride (HgF 4) has been taken by some to reinforce the view that the group 12 elements should be considered transition metals, but some authors still consider this compound to be exceptional.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Even in bare dications, Cn2+ is predicted to be 6d87s2, unlike Hg2+ which is 5d106s0.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Although meitnerium, darmstadtium, and roentgenium are within the d-block and are expected to behave as transition metals analogous to their lighter congeners iridium, platinum, and gold, this has not yet been experimentally confirmed.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Whether copernicium behaves more like mercury or has properties more similar to those of the noble gas radon is not clear.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Relative inertness of Cn would come from the relativistically expanded 7s–7p1/2 energy gap, which is already adumbrated in the 6s–6p1/2 gap for Hg, weakening metallic bonding and causing its well-known low melting and boiling points.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Transition metals with lower or higher group numbers are described as 'earlier' or 'later', respectively.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] When described in a two-way classification scheme, early transition metals are on the left side of the d-block from group 3 to group 7.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Late transition metals are on the right side of the d-block, from group 8 to 11 (or 12, if they are counted as transition metals).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In an alternative three-way scheme, groups 3, 4, and 5 are classified as early transition metals, 6, 7, and 8 are classified as middle transition metals, and 9, 10, and 11 (and sometimes group 12) are classified as late transition metals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The heavy group 2 elements calcium, strontium, and barium do not have filled d-orbitals as single atoms, but are known to have d-orbital bonding participation in some compounds, and for that reason have been called "honorary" transition metals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The f-block elements La–Yb and Ac–No have chemical activity of the (n−1)d shell, but importantly also have chemical activity of the (n−2)f shell that is absent in d-block elements.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Hence they are often treated separately as inner transition elements.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The general electronic configuration of the d-block atoms is [noble gas](*n* − 1)d0–10*n*s0–2*n*p0–1.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Here "[noble gas]" is the electronic configuration of the last noble gas preceding the atom in question, and *n* is the highest principal quantum number of an occupied orbital in that atom.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] For example, Ti (*Z* = 22) is in period 4 so that *n* = 4, the first 18 electrons have the same configuration of Ar at the end of period 3, and the overall configuration is [Ar]3d24s2.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The period 6 and 7 transition metals also add core (*n* − 2)f14 electrons, which are omitted from the tables below.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The p orbitals are almost never filled in free atoms (the one exception being lawrencium due to relativistic effects that become important at such high *Z*), but they can contribute to the chemical bonding in transition metal compounds.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The Madelung rule predicts that the inner d orbital is filled after the valence-shell s orbital.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The typical electronic structure of transition metal atoms is then written as [noble gas]*n*s2(*n* − 1)d*m*.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] This rule is approximate, but holds for most of the transition metals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Even when it fails for the neutral ground state, it accurately describes a low-lying excited state.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The d subshell is the next-to-last subshell and is denoted as (*n* − 1)d subshell.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The number of s electrons in the outermost s subshell is generally one or two except palladium (Pd), with no electron in that s sub shell in its ground state.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The s subshell in the valence shell is represented as the *n*s subshell, e.g.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In the periodic table, the transition metals are present in ten groups (3 to 12).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The elements in group 3 have an *n*s2(*n* − 1)d1 configuration, except for lawrencium (Lr): its 7s27p1 configuration exceptionally does not fill the 6d orbitals at all.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The first transition series is present in the 4th period, and starts after Ca (*Z* = 20) of group 2 with the configuration [Ar]4s2, or scandium (Sc), the first element of group 3 with atomic number *Z* = 21 and configuration [Ar]4s23d1, depending on the definition used.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] As we move from left to right, electrons are added to the same d subshell till it is complete.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Since the electrons added fill the (*n* − 1)d orbitals, the properties of the d-block elements are quite different from those of s and p block elements in which the filling occurs either in s or in p orbitals of the valence shell.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] A careful look at the electronic configuration of the elements reveals that there are certain exceptions to the Madelung rule.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] For Cr as an example the rule predicts the configuration 3d44s2, but the observed atomic spectra show that the real ground state is 3d54s1.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] To explain such exceptions, it is necessary to consider the effects of increasing nuclear charge on the orbital energies, as well as the electron–electron interactions including both Coulomb repulsion and exchange energy.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The exceptions are in any case not very relevant for chemistry because the energy difference between them and the expected configuration is always quite low.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The (*n* − 1)d orbitals that are involved in the transition metals are very significant because they influence such properties as magnetic character, variable oxidation states, formation of coloured compounds etc.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The valence s and p orbitals (*n*s and *n*p) have very little contribution in this regard since they hardly change in the moving from left to the right in a transition series.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In transition metals, there are greater horizontal similarities in the properties of the elements in a period in comparison to the periods in which the d orbitals are not involved.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] This is because in a transition series, the valence shell electronic configuration of the elements do not change.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] However, there are some group similarities as well.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] There are a number of properties shared by the transition elements that are not found in other elements, which results from the partially filled d shell.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Most transition metals can be bound to a variety of ligands, allowing for a wide variety of transition metal complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Colour in transition-series metal compounds is generally due to electronic transitions of two principal types.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] A metal-to-ligand charge transfer (MLCT) transition will be most likely when the metal is in a low oxidation state and the ligand is easily reduced.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In general charge transfer transitions result in more intense colours than d–d transitions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In centrosymmetric complexes, such as octahedral complexes, d–d transitions are forbidden by the Laporte rule and only occur because of vibronic coupling in which a molecular vibration occurs together with a d–d transition.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Tetrahedral complexes have somewhat more intense colour because mixing d and p orbitals is possible when there is no centre of symmetry, so transitions are not pure d–d transitions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The molar absorptivity (ε) of bands caused by d–d transitions are relatively low, roughly in the range 5–500 M−1cm−1 (where M = mol dm−3).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Some d–d transitions are spin forbidden.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] An example occurs in octahedral, high-spin complexes of manganese(II), which has a d5 configuration in which all five electrons have parallel spins; the colour of such complexes is much weaker than in complexes with spin-allowed transitions.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Many compounds of manganese(II) appear almost colourless.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The spectrum of [Mn(H 2O) 6]2+ shows a maximum molar absorptivity of about 0.04 M−1cm−1 in the visible spectrum.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] A characteristic of transition metals is that they exhibit two or more oxidation states, usually differing by one.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] For example, compounds of vanadium are known in all oxidation states between −1, such as [V(CO) 6]− , and +5, such as VO3− 4.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Main-group elements in groups 13 to 18 also exhibit multiple oxidation states.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The "common" oxidation states of these elements typically differ by two instead of one.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] For example, compounds of gallium in oxidation states +1 and +3 exist in which there is a single gallium atom.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Compounds of Ga(II) would have an unpaired electron and would behave as a free radical and generally be destroyed rapidly, but some stable radicals of Ga(II) are known.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Gallium also has a formal oxidation state of +2 in dimeric compounds, such as [Ga 2Cl 6]2− , which contain a Ga-Ga bond formed from the unpaired electron on each Ga atom.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Thus the main difference in oxidation states, between transition elements and other elements is that oxidation states are known in which there is a single atom of the element and one or more unpaired electrons.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The maximum oxidation state in the first row transition metals is equal to the number of valence electrons from titanium (+4) up to manganese (+7), but decreases in the later elements.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In the second row, the maximum occurs with ruthenium (+8), and in the third row, the maximum occurs with iridium (+9).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In compounds such as [MnO 4]− and OsO 4, the elements achieve a stable configuration by covalent bonding.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The lowest oxidation states are exhibited in metal carbonyl complexes such as Cr(CO) 6 (oxidation state zero) and [Fe(CO) 4]2− (oxidation state −2) in which the 18-electron rule is obeyed.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Ionic compounds are mostly formed with oxidation states +2 and +3.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In aqueous solution, the ions are hydrated by (usually) six water molecules arranged octahedrally.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Transition metal compounds are paramagnetic when they have one or more unpaired d electrons.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In octahedral complexes with between four and seven d electrons both high spin and low spin states are possible.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Tetrahedral transition metal complexes such as [FeCl 4]2− are high spin because the crystal field splitting is small so that the energy to be gained by virtue of the electrons being in lower energy orbitals is always less than the energy needed to pair up the spins.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] These include octahedral, low-spin, d6 and square-planar d8 complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In these cases, crystal field splitting is such that all the electrons are paired up.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Ferromagnetism occurs when individual atoms are paramagnetic and the spin vectors are aligned parallel to each other in a crystalline material.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Metallic iron and the alloy alnico are examples of ferromagnetic materials involving transition metals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Antiferromagnetism is another example of a magnetic property arising from a particular alignment of individual spins in the solid state.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] The transition metals and their compounds are known for their homogeneous and heterogeneous catalytic activity.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] This activity is ascribed to their ability to adopt multiple oxidation states and to form complexes.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Vanadium(V) oxide (in the contact process), finely divided iron (in the Haber process), and nickel (in catalytic hydrogenation) are some of the examples.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Catalysts at a solid surface (nanomaterial-based catalysts) involve the formation of bonds between reactant molecules and atoms of the surface of the catalyst (first row transition metals utilize 3d and 4s electrons for bonding).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] This has the effect of increasing the concentration of the reactants at the catalyst surface and also weakening of the bonds in the reacting molecules (the activation energy is lowered).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Also because the transition metal ions can change their oxidation states, they become more effective as catalysts.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] An interesting type of catalysis occurs when the products of a reaction catalyse the reaction producing more catalyst (autocatalysis).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] One example is the reaction of oxalic acid with acidified potassium permanganate (or manganate (VII)).
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Once a little Mn2+ has been produced, it can react with MnO4− forming Mn3+.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] This then reacts with C2O4− ions forming Mn2+ again.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] As implied by the name, all transition metals are metals and thus conductors of electricity.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] In general, transition metals possess a high density and high melting points and boiling points.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] These properties are due to metallic bonding by delocalized d electrons, leading to cohesion which increases with the number of shared electrons.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] However the group 12 metals have much lower melting and boiling points since their full d subshells prevent d–d bonding, which again tends to differentiate them from the accepted transition metals.
[src:inorganic-chemistry/transition-metal] Mercury has a melting point of −38.83 °C (−37.89 °F) and is a liquid at room temperature.
